c and sociological analysis to underscore the movement and change that fueled the powerful narratives defining the century, the city, and their literature. In her understanding and reconstruction of the guidebooks of Mercier, Hugo, Vallès, and others, alongside the novels of Flaubert, Hugo, Vallès, and Zola, Ferguson reveals that these works are themselves revolutionary performances, ones that challenged the modernizing city even as they transcribed its emergence.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCities and towns in literature. 0aCity and town life in literature. 0aFrench literaturey19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aFrench literaturezFrancezParisxHistory and criticism. 0aLiterature and historyzFrancezParisxHistoryy19th century. 0aPolitics and literaturezFrancezParisxHistoryy19th century. 0aRevolutionary literature, FrenchxHistory and criticism. 0aRevolutions in literature. 4aEuropean history. 4aFrance. 4aFrench Revolution. 4ahistory of revolutions. 4ahistory. 4arevolution. 7aHISTORY / Europe / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052032299840uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520323001?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520323001423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520323001/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles